/*
Problem: Longest Subarray with Sum K (Only Positive Numbers)
Similar LeetCode: No official equivalent.
*/

class Solution {
public:
    int longestSubarray(vector<int>& arr, int k) {
        int l = 0;
        int r = 0;
        int sum = 0;
        int ans = 0;

        while (r < arr.size()) {
            sum += arr[r];

            while (sum > k) {
                sum -= arr[l];
                l++;
            }

            if (sum == k) {
                ans = max(ans, r - l + 1);
            }

            r++;
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

/*
Time Complexity:
O(n)

Space Complexity:
O(1)

---------------------------------------------------------
Important Notes
---------------------------------------------------------

1. This approach works ONLY when all array elements are positive.

2. Why Sliding Window works?
   - Adding a new element always increases the sum.
   - Removing an element always decreases the sum.
   This monotonic property is necessary for Sliding Window.

3. Sliding Window Rules:

   sum < k
       -> Expand Window
       -> r++

   sum > k
       -> Shrink Window
       -> sum -= arr[l]
       -> l++

   sum == k
       -> Update answer
       -> Continue expanding (r++)

4. Why while(sum > k) instead of if(sum > k)?

   Example:
   arr = [2,2,2,2]
   k = 2

   Window = [2,2,2]
   sum = 6

   Removing one element:
   sum = 4

   Still greater than k.

   Therefore we must keep shrinking until:
   sum <= k

5. Golden Rule:

   Left Pointer (l) always moves forward.
   Right Pointer (r) always moves forward.

   Never:
       l--
       r--

   Otherwise the same element gets processed multiple times,
   breaking O(n) complexity.

6. Why O(n)?

   Every element:
   - Enters the window exactly once (r).
   - Leaves the window at most once (l).

   Hence each element is visited at most twice.

7. This approach FAILS if negative numbers are present.

   Example:
   arr = [2, -1, 2]

   Removing -1 increases the sum,
   so Sliding Window no longer works.

   In that case use:
   Prefix Sum + HashMap.

---------------------------------------------------------
My Mistakes / Misconceptions
---------------------------------------------------------

1. Initially thought that when sum > k,
   moving r-- would reduce the sum.

   Wrong.

   Sliding Window never moves pointers backward.

2. Learned that only l should move when sum > k,
   because we need to remove elements from the current window.

3. Initially overlooked why while(sum > k) is used.

   Learned that removing one element may still leave
   sum > k, so repeated shrinking is required.

4. Learned an important Sliding Window property:

   Both pointers always move only in the forward direction.

---------------------------------------------------------
Concepts Learned
---------------------------------------------------------

✔ Sliding Window
✔ Two Pointers
✔ Window Expansion
✔ Window Shrinking
✔ Monotonic Property of Positive Arrays
✔ Why Sliding Window fails for Negative Numbers
✔ O(n) Traversal using Two Pointers
*/
